<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-316-850  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 316 850.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IBM System User  March 1990 pS20(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The big pay-off. (benefits of computerizing a business) (Nodesupplement)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A report on the cost and benefits of the automation of all or partof a business can bring from a 10 to 1,000 percent return,depending on the approach taken.andP;  The estimated return on computersystem development is based on computerizing a task, a workprocess or an entire way of doing business.andP;  Traditionally,automation has meant task automation and the expected savings inlower personnel costs and/or higher productivity frequently do notmaterialize or are less than expected.andP;  While the payback fromtask transformation may be only 20 percent, the payback from workprocess transformation may be as high as 200 percent when a flowof information is automated.andP;  Transformation through rethinkingand computerizing a entire way of doing business may give returnsas high as 1,000 percent, particularly when it provides access tonew markets and other business opportunities.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     AutomationReportsCost Benefit AnalysisSystem Development.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   The four phases of computerization. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>